{
 "cells": [
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "# Overview\r\n\r\nLet $\\theta_i$ be a parameter in the set $\\theta$ that defines all the variables that affect the output of a forward model. $\\theta$ represents the true but unknown values of these parameters. We call $\\theta$ the parameter space.\r\nAn estimator $d(\\chi)$ attempts to estimate these values given a set of observations $\\chi$. The result of the estimation is the estimation space $\\hat{\\theta}$.\r\nAn estimator is considered unbiased given\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe goal is to define the lowest uncertainty (variance) score possible under the assumption of an unbiased estimator. \r\nIt is important to note that a true unbiased estimator is intractable due to physical limitations so this provides the absolute unrealistically best case.\r\n\r\nWe must also establish the generator for the observation space $\\chi$. The forward model $g(\\theta, \\chi)$ defines a function $g$ that maps $\\theta$ to $\\chi$.\r\nIf we take $\\chi$ to be a set of sampled points with probability distribution $f$ then we can likewise treat $g$ as itself a probability distribution. \r\nThen we say that \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$g: \\theta \\to \\chi, \\quad \\theta \\mapsto \\mathbb{E} \\left[f\\right]$$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(* 1. Define the Forward Model g as a function of theta and x *)\r\n(* For now, we keep it generic: g[\\[Theta], x] *)\r\nforwardModel = g[\\[Theta], x];\r\n\r\n(* 2. Define the 'unbiasedness' property *)\r\n(* This is a symbolic representation of E[d(x)] = \\[Theta] *)\r\nunbiasedCondition = Expectation[d[x], x \\[Distributed] dist] == \\[Theta];\r\n\r\n",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {
    "timing": {
     "startTime": 1777742281618,
     "endTime": 1777742281918
    },
    "executionOrder": 6,
    "success": true
   }
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "# CMOS Derivation\r\n\r\nFollowing the model laid out by Gerwe & Idell (2003), the rigorous static CMOS model calculates the expected photon flux at a specific focal-plane-array (FPA) element $(x, y)$. It is the convolution of the projected source intensity $I$ and the Point Spread Function (PSF), integrated over the physical area of the pixel $\\mathcal{A}_{x,y}$, plus a background rate $b$:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn the case of a single sub-diffraction point source, the source intensity $I$ is modeled as $N\\delta$ where $N = \\text{Flux} \\times \\text{Time}$. The convolution of a delta function with the PSF evaluates directly to the PSF itself at location $(\\xi, \\eta)$. Assuming the pixel size is small relative to the PSF, or that our discrete PSF function already accounts for pixel integration, the forward model simplifies to a direct scaling of the PSF evaluated at the pixel center:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$g: \\theta \\to \\chi, \\quad \\theta \\mapsto \\mathbb{E} \\left[f\\right]$$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWe restrict the derivation in this case to localization in 3D space. That is $\\theta = \\left\\{x, y, z\\right\\}$. Then the physically ideal model for $I$ is a point source, justifying our use of the simplified case for the remainder of the derivation.\r\n\r\nTo perform 3D localization, our forward model must encode the axial depth parameter $z_c$. In standard optical systems, depth is encoded through defocus blur. As a point source moves away from the sensor's focal plane ($z=0$), the projected spot of light expands. We model the Point Spread Function as a 2D Gaussian whose variance $\\sigma^2$ is a function of depth $z_c$:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhere: $\\sigma_0$ is the beam waist, representing the minimum blur radius when the object is perfectly in focus. $Z_R$ is the Rayleigh Range, a parameter characterizing the camera's depth of field. It dictates how rapidly the blur expands as the object moves out of focus. By substituting this depth-dependent $\\sigma(z_c)$ into our point-source forward model, the likelihood function becomes directly dependent on $z_c$, allowing us to calculate the Cramér-Rao Lower Bound for depth estimation.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* The Simplified (Point Source) Model *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\n(* 0. Define depth-dependent blur width (Critical for Z-axis FIM) *)\r\n\\[Sigma][zc_] := \\[Sigma]0 * Sqrt[1 + (zc / zR)^2];\r\n\r\n(* 1. Define the PSF symbolically using \\[Sigma][zc] *)\r\npsf[x_, y_, xc_, yc_, zc_] := (1 / (2 * Pi * \\[Sigma][zc]^2)) * Exp[-((x - xc)^2 + (y - yc)^2) / (2 * \\[Sigma][zc]^2)];\r\n\r\n(* 2. Define the Forward Model *)\r\ngSimple[x_, y_, xc_, yc_, zc_] := Nphotons * psf[x, y, xc, yc, zc] + background;\r\n\r\n(* 3. Define how the gradient is calculated *)\r\ngradG[var_] := D[gSimple[x, y, xc, yc, zc], var];\r\n\r\n(* 4. Define the parameter list for indexing *)\r\n\\[Theta] = {xc, yc, zc};",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {
    "timing": {
     "startTime": 1777742281920,
     "endTime": 1777742281979
    },
    "executionOrder": 19,
    "success": true
   }
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "To define a lower bound, we must first define the Fisher Information Matrix for the forward model. The noise for the model is defined as being a linear combination of shot noise from a Poisson distribution, and readout noise sampled from a Gaussian distribution. Owing to the difficulty of defining a PDF that accurately encapsulates both distributions, Gerwe & Idell approximate the noise model $d$ as: \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWe take their lead and arrive at the resulting Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) defined as:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$g: \\theta \\to \\chi, \\quad \\theta \\mapsto \\mathbb{E} \\left[f\\right]$$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nwhere $\\sigma_r$ often abbreviated simply to $\\sigma$, is the readout noise.\r\n\r\nWhile the sensor array is discrete, deriving a closed-form analytical expression for the CRLB is mathematically tractable if we approximate the sum over individual pixels as a continuous double integral over the sensor plane $\\mathbb{R}^2$. Assuming the pixel dimensions are sufficiently small compared to the PSF (Nyquist criterion), the discrete Fisher Information Matrix can be approximated continuously as:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "mime": "text/markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* 4. Continuous Fisher Information Matrix    *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\nfimContinuous[i_, j_] := Integrate[\r\n  (gradG[\\[Theta][[i]]] * gradG[\\[Theta][[j]]]) / (gSimple[x, y, xc, yc, zc] + readNoiseVar),\r\n  {x, -Infinity, Infinity}, \r\n  {y, -Infinity, Infinity},\r\n  Assumptions - {\\[Sigma]0  0, zR  0, Nphotons  0, readNoiseVar = 0}\r\n]\r\n\r\n(* NOTE: We DO NOT evaluate fimContinuous[1,1] directly here! *)\r\n(* Mathematica will hang trying to find a closed-form solution. *)\r\n(* We skip directly to evaluating the physical limits in the next block. *)\r\n\r\n(* InfoXX = fimContinuous[1, 1]; *)\r\n(* InfoYY = fimContinuous[2, 2]; *)\r\n(* InfoZZ = fimContinuous[3, 3]; *)",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {
    "timing": {
     "startTime": 1777742281980,
     "endTime": 1777742282030
    },
    "executionOrder": 29,
    "success": true
   }
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "We evaluate the FIM entry for the $X$-coordinate, $I_{xx}$. First, we compute the partial derivative of the forward model with respect to $x_c$:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSubstituting this into our continuous integral, we get the exact analytical form for the Fisher Information:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$g: \\theta \\to \\chi, \\quad \\theta \\mapsto \\mathbb{E} \\left[f\\right]$$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhere $\\beta = b + \\sigma_r^2$ is the total background variance per pixel. Because this integral lacks a simple closed-form solution, we evaluate it at the two defining physical limits of the sensor:\r\n\r\n1. The Photon-Noise Limit ($\\beta \\to 0$): When the signal vastly overpowers the background read noise, the $\\beta$ term vanishes. The $N \\cdot \\text{PSF}$ terms partially cancel, yielding:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTherefore, the best possible localization variance is $\\text{Var}(\\hat{x}_c) \\ge \\frac{\\sigma(z_c)^2}{N}$.\r\n\r\n2. The Background-Noise Limit ($\\beta \\gg N \\cdot \\text{PSF}$): When the background noise dominates (e.g., low light or extreme defocus), the denominator is approximately $\\beta$. The integral over $\\text{PSF}^2$ evaluates to $\\frac{1}{4\\pi\\sigma(z_c)^2}$, yielding:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$g: \\theta \\to \\chi, \\quad \\theta \\mapsto \\mathbb{E} \\left[f\\right]$$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTherefore, the localization variance scales with the square of the photon count: $\\text{Var}(\\hat{x}_c) \\ge \\frac{8 \\pi \\sigma(z_c)^4 \\beta}{N^2}$.\r\n\r\nYou can see the analytical results in the cell below. The first 2 equations represent the fisher information for signal and background regimes specifically, and the final 2 are the lower bounds for the same.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "mime": "text/markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* 5. Evaluating FIM Limits for InfoXX        *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\n(* Let's define the total background noise \\[Beta] *)\r\n\\[Beta] = background + readNoiseVar;\r\n\r\n(* The squared gradient for X from our earlier calculation *)\r\ngradXSquared = FullSimplify[gradG[xc]^2];\r\n\r\n(* Limit 1: Photon-Noise Limited (\\[Beta] - 0) *)\r\n(* We substitute \\[Beta] = 0 directly into the denominator *)\r\nintegrandPhoton = FullSimplify[gradXSquared / (Nphotons * psf[x, y, xc, yc, zc])];\r\n\r\nInfoXXPhoton = Integrate[\r\n  integrandPhoton, \r\n  {x, -Infinity, Infinity}, {y, -Infinity, Infinity},\r\n  Assumptions - {\\[Sigma]0  0, zR  0, Nphotons  0, zc \\[Element] Reals}\r\n]\r\n\r\n(* Limit 2: Background-Noise Limited (\\[Beta] dominates) *)\r\n(* We approximate the denominator as just \\[Beta] *)\r\nintegrandBackground = FullSimplify[gradXSquared / \\[Beta]];\r\n\r\nInfoXXBackground = Integrate[\r\n  integrandBackground, \r\n  {x, -Infinity, Infinity}, {y, -Infinity, Infinity},\r\n  Assumptions - {\\[Sigma]0  0, zR  0, Nphotons  0, \\[Beta]  0, zc \\[Element] Reals}\r\n]\r\n\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* 6. The Cramér-Rao Lower Bounds (CRLB)      *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\n(* The CRLB is the inverse of the Fisher Information *)\r\nCRLBXphoton = 1 / InfoXXPhoton\r\nCRLBXbackground = 1 / InfoXXBackground",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "mime": "text/markdown",
   "outputs": [
    {
     "items": [
      {
       "data": "<div class=\"wexpr\"><wgraph class=\"resizable\" style=\"width:59.4px;height:24.6px;\" aspect-ratio=\"0.414141\" tabIndex=\"-1\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></wgraph></div>",
       "mime": "x-application/wolfram-language-html"
