  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "# Conclusion (CMOS)\r\n\r\nEvaluation of the depth Cramér-Rao Lower Bounds ($CRLB_Z$) reveals two fundamental properties of standard optical CMOS tracking:\r\n\r\n1. The Depth Dead Zone: Both the photon-limited and background-limited bounds for depth contain a $z_c^2$ term in the denominator. As the target approaches the exact focal plane ($z_c \\to 0$), the CRLB approaches infinity. Because a standard PSF expands symmetrically on either side of the focal plane, its spatial derivative at the focus is zero. This fundamental blindness to focal-plane depth variations motivates the need for PSF engineering to break axial symmetry.\r\n\r\n2. Asymptotic Scaling Laws: Outside of the dead zone, the lower bounds for both lateral ($x, y$) and axial ($z$) localization follow strict asymptotic scaling laws with respect to the total photon count $N$ (where $N \\propto \\text{Integration Time } T$):\r\n\r\n    * Photon-Noise Limit: When the signal dominates the background ($\\beta \\to 0$), the localization variance scales as $\\mathcal{O}(N^{-1})$. Consequently, the Standard Error (the absolute tracking precision) scales as $\\mathcal{O}(N^{-1/2})$.\r\n    \r\n    * Background-Noise Limit: When the background noise dominates, the variance scales as $\\mathcal{O}(N^{-2})$, causing the Standard Error to scale as $\\mathcal{O}(N^{-1})$.These standard scaling limits serve as the baseline against which novel neuromorphic and differential sensors must be compared.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "# The Event Sensor\r\n\r\nThe event sensor operates on a fundamentally different principle than traditional image sensors. Whereas traditional sensors capture charge induced by incoming photons into electron wells and integrate that charge over a fixed exposure window to create a final image, event sensors—often referred to as Dynamic Vision Sensors (DVS)—respond to local changes in light at discrete moments in continuous time with logarithmic sensitivity. \r\nDVS pixels fire asynchronously whenever the absolute change in log-intensity crosses a set hardware threshold $\\mathcal{T}$. *(Note: In practice, there are typically two distinct thresholds—one for a positive change (\"ON\" event) and one for a negative change (\"OFF\" event). For this derivation, we assume a symmetrical threshold value for simplicity. This assumption does not change the underlying mathematics or the asymptotic result).*\r\n\r\nThe most information a single event spike can provide is the spatial coordinate $(x,y)$, the microsecond timestamp $t$, and the polarity (direction) of the intensity change. Taken on its own, a single event offers very little structural information. However, when integrated (binned) over a period of time, Shah et al. (2024) have shown that the resulting event frame mathematically approximates the logarithmic difference of intensity over that same period:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn their work, they define a Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) for a sensor with a specific set of parameters and derive the Cramér-Rao lower bound for 3D tracking. Here, we follow their statistical framework, extending it to a generalized analytical result to evaluate the scaling limits for any integration time $T$ for which their Normal-approximation assumptions hold.\r\n",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "# Event Frame Generation and Intensity Parameters\r\n\r\nTo rigorously define the Fisher Information for the event sensor, we must first establish the parameters that govern the generation of the event frame $E$. Let $I(x,y,t)$ be the continuous instantaneous photon flux incident on pixel $(x,y)$ at time $t$.Because event sensors trigger on temporal contrast, the measurement depends not only on the static position of the target but on its dynamics over a macroscopic integration interval $\\tau$. Following the Shah et al. framework, we parameterize the changing light signal during this interval using two macroscopic intensity variables:$\\mu$ (Base Intensity): The expected number of photons arriving at the pixel during the interval if the target were stationary. This serves as the baseline illumination and is mathematically identical to our noiseless static CMOS forward model: $\\mu = g_s(x,y \\mid \\theta)$.$\\nu$ (Intensity Difference): The expected change in the photon count over the interval $\\tau$ due strictly to the target's motion or state change. This is driven by the temporal derivative of the forward model.The Statistical Challenge and Hardware QuantizationIf standard image capture is a Poisson process dependent on $\\mu$, an event frame represents the logarithmic difference between two such processes. If we subdivide the integration interval $\\tau$ into $K$ infinitesimally small steps, the total change in log-intensity $\\Delta L$ is the sum of the changes across each step. That is:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhere $\\lambda_k$ is the expected photon flux at step $k$. Assuming the time interval between steps is sufficiently small, the ratio $\\frac{\\lambda_k}{\\lambda_{k-1}}$ is near unity. Applying the first-order Taylor expansion $\\log(x) \\approx x - 1$, we obtain:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$g: \\theta \\to \\chi, \\quad \\theta \\mapsto \\mathbb{E} \\left[f\\right]$$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWe define the change in expected intensity during a step as $\\Delta \\lambda_k = \\lambda_k - \\lambda_{k-1}$. Because photon arrivals follow a Poisson process, $\\Delta \\lambda_k$ is treated as a Poisson random variable. Assuming the base intensity $\\lambda_{k-1}$ is large and relatively constant over the step, the sum of these independent random variables converges.However, unlike an ideal continuous sensor, a physical Event Camera only registers an event when the log-intensity change crosses a discrete hardware threshold $\\mathcal{T}$. This discrete triggering introduces quantization noise into the accumulated measurement. Modeling this quantization error as a uniform distribution bounded by the threshold yields a static variance term $\\sigma_q^2 \\approx \\mathcal{T}^2 / T$.Transitioning back to our macroscopic parameters $\\mu$ and $\\nu$, and incorporating this hardware quantization limit, the accumulated log-intensity change $\\Delta L$ over the entire interval $\\tau$ can be approximated as a Normal distribution:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n$$ \\mathbb{E} (\\hat{\\theta} - \\theta) = 0 $$\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis Normal approximation provides a tractable Probability Density Function (PDF) that encapsulates the signal-dependent Poisson noise of the incident light, the differential nature of the event sensor, and the discrete quantization noise of the hardware.",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {},
   "executionSummary": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* 9. The Event Sensor Statistical Model      *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\n(* Define the Macroscopic Parameters for the Normal Approximation *)\r\n(* \\[Mu] is the base expected photon count over the interval *)\r\n(* \\[Nu] is the expected difference in photon count over the interval *)\r\n(* \\[Sigma]q^2 is the static quantization noise from the hardware threshold *)\r\n\r\neventMean = \\[Nu] / \\[Mu];\r\neventVariance = \\[Nu] / \\[Mu]^2 + \\[Sigma]q^2;\r\neventStdDev = Sqrt[eventVariance];\r\n\r\n(* Define the Event Distribution *)\r\neventDist = NormalDistribution[eventMean, eventStdDev];\r\n\r\n(* Calculate the Log-Likelihood of observing a specific log-intensity change 'deltaL' *)\r\neventLogLikelihood = FullSimplify[Log[PDF[eventDist, deltaL]], Assumptions -> {\\[Nu] > 0, \\[Mu] > 0, \\[Sigma]q > 0}];\r\n\r\n\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* 10. The Event Sensor Scores                *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\n(* The Score is the sensitivity of the log-likelihood to changes in the parameters *)\r\nscoreMu = FullSimplify[D[eventLogLikelihood, \\[Mu]]];\r\nscoreNu = FullSimplify[D[eventLogLikelihood, \\[Nu]]];\r\n\r\n\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n(* 11. The Event Sensor Fisher Information    *)\r\n(* ========================================== *)\r\n\r\n(* The FIM is the Expected Value of the outer product of the Scores *)\r\n(* Because deltaL follows eventDist, we use Mathematica's Expectation function *)\r\n\r\nFIMEventMuMu = FullSimplify[Expectation[scoreMu^2, deltaL \\[Distributed] eventDist], Assumptions -> {\\[Nu] > 0, \\[Mu] > 0, \\[Sigma]q > 0}]\r\nFIMEventNuNu = FullSimplify[Expectation[scoreNu^2, deltaL \\[Distributed] eventDist], Assumptions -> {\\[Nu] > 0, \\[Mu] > 0, \\[Sigma]q > 0}]\r\nFIMEventMuNu = FullSimplify[Expectation[scoreMu * scoreNu, deltaL \\[Distributed] eventDist], Assumptions -> {\\[Nu] > 0, \\[Mu] > 0, \\[Sigma]q > 0}]\r\n\r\n(* Assemble the 2x2 Macroscopic Fisher Information Matrix *)\r\neventMacroscopicFIM = {\r\n  {FIMEventMuMu, FIMEventMuNu},\r\n  {FIMEventMuNu, FIMEventNuNu}\r\n};\r\n\r\nMatrixForm[eventMacroscopicFIM]",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
